=======================================================================================
Sequential and Parrallel Runner Differences
==============================================================================================
🌟 Elementary summary

    Sequential: Slower, but uses one runner → cheaper in terms of concurrency.

    Parallel: Faster, but multiple runners run at once → same total minutes, but can feel more expensive if you’re billed per concurrent runner.

👉 If you’re on GitHub’s free tier, you get a set number of minutes per month. Parallel jobs don’t increase the total minutes used, but they do increase concurrent usage. If you’re on a paid plan where concurrency is billed separately, then yes, parallelism can attract more fees.

Would you like me to sketch a hybrid workflow where lint/test run in parallel (fast feedback), but build runs sequentially (to save runner concurrency)? That way you balance speed and cost.

